text: The case underscores the complexity of domestic abuse, how women are terrified that reporting abuse could cause them to lose their children and fact that many care for the man who is abusing them. Prosecutors think, in hindsight, Cisneros’s case as having been avoidable.
author: katiezez

text: A little more than a year later, Cisneros was dead. Authorities said her abuser shot her once in the chest on Christmas morning 2015. The child she was pregnant with when she went to the hospital was sleeping beside her.
author: katiezez

text: Months, later the case was reassigned. The common-law husband was taken into custody and Cisneros visited the DA’s office. She was adamant she was safe and wanted the case against him dismissed. A grand jury listened and didn’t indict him.
author: katiezez

text: The hospital contacted authorities, but the case stalled. Child protective services opened an inquiry into Cisneros, alleging she failed to protect her two older children from witnessing the abuse she suffered. She took a class on how to manage her husband’s violent behavior.
author: katiezez

text: Cisneros arrived at a Fort Worth hospital with a bloody nose, busted lip, strangulation marks on her neck and blood in her eyes. Her common-law husband allegedly tried to strangle her into unconsciousness. She was eight months pregnant.
